---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import PageHeader from '../../components/PageHeader.astro';
import { languages, useTranslations, type Lang } from '../../i18n/ui';

/** All non-English locales get their own /<lang>/guide. The English copy
 * lives in the root /guide.astro. */
export function getStaticPaths() {
	return languages
		.filter((l) => l.code !== 'en')
		.map((l) => ({ params: { lang: l.code } }));
}

const { lang } = Astro.params;
const langCode: Lang = (
	lang && languages.some((l) => l.code === lang) ? lang : 'en'
) as Lang;
const t = useTranslations(langCode);
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
const homeHref = `${base}/${langCode}/`;

const sections = [
	{ id: 'intro', title: '1. Introduction' },
	{ id: 'concepts', title: '2. Concepts' },
	{ id: 'install', title: '3. Install' },
	{ id: 'config', title: '4. Configuration' },
	{ id: 'plugins', title: '5. Plugins' },
	{ id: 'capabilities', title: '6. Tools / Prompts / Resources / Knowledge' },
	{ id: 'skills', title: '7. Skills' },
	{ id: 'i18n', title: '8. i18n' },
	{ id: 'quality', title: '9. Quality gates & multi-language' },
	{ id: 'extending', title: '10. Extending mcp-vertex' },
	{ id: 'tokens', title: '11. Token budgets' },
	{ id: 'transitions', title: '12. View transitions' },
	{ id: 'faq', title: '13. FAQ' },
];
---

<Base lang={langCode} title={`Guide — @mcp-vertex/core`} description="A detailed walkthrough of the @mcp-vertex/core project: concepts, install, config, plugins, quality gates, extending, FAQ.">
	<PageHeader lang={langCode} title="Guide" />
	<section class="section">
		<div class="container guide">
			<aside class="guide__toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
				<strong>Contents</strong>
				<ol>
					{sections.map((s) => (
						<li><a href={`#${s.id}`}>{s.title}</a></li>
					))}
				</ol>
			</aside>
			<article class="guide__body">
				{langCode !== 'en' && (
					<p class="guide__notice">
						⚠ This guide is in <strong>English</strong>. Translations for {langCode} are
						pending — see <a href={`${homeHref}`}>the home page</a> for what's translated so far.
					</p>
				)}
				<h2 id="intro">1. Introduction</h2>
				<p>
					<code>@mcp-vertex/core</code> is a project-agnostic <strong>Model Context Protocol</strong>
					server core + CLI plugin loader. The core knows nothing about your domain; capabilities
					ship as plugins you load on demand. The same plugin behaves identically under any
					host, IDE, or model.
				</p>

				<h2 id="concepts">2. Concepts</h2>
				<ul>
					<li><strong>Core</strong>: a small MCP server that registers tools, prompts, resources, knowledge.</li>
					<li><strong>Plugin</strong>: an npm package exporting <code>IMcpPlugin</code>. Adds tools, prompts, knowledge, or skills.</li>
					<li><strong>Preset</strong>: a curated list of plugins (<code>minimal</code>, <code>standard</code>, <code>swarm</code>).</li>
					<li><strong>Capability</strong>: a tool, prompt, resource or knowledge entry exposed by a plugin.</li>
					<li><strong>Token budget</strong>: a measured ceiling on the bytes the server emits per response. A CI test guards regressions.</li>
				</ul>

				<h2 id="install">3. Install</h2>
				<p>See <a href={`${base}/install`}>the install page</a> for the full matrix. TL;DR:</p>
				<pre><code>{`# bun
bunx @mcp-vertex/core init
bunx @mcp-vertex/core --check`}</code></pre>

				<h2 id="config">4. Configuration</h2>
				<p>
					Place a <code>mcp-vertex.config.json</code> at the workspace root. The
					loader auto-detects it. Schema lives at
					<code>packages/core/schema/mcp-vertex.config.schema.json</code>.
				</p>
				<pre><code>{`{
  "cacheDir": ".cache/mcp-vertex",
  "docsDir": "docs/mcp-vertex",
  "plugins": {
    "memory": { "options": { "ttlSeconds": 86400 } },
    "proposals": { "prefix": "work" }
  }
}`}</code></pre>

				<h2 id="plugins">5. Plugins</h2>
				<p>
					There are 10 official plugins. See the
					<a href={`${base}/plugins`}>plugin index</a> for the live list.
				</p>

				<h2 id="capabilities">6. Tools / Prompts / Resources / Knowledge</h2>
				<p>
					Each plugin can contribute any of the four capability types. The
					<a href={`${base}/tools`}>tools page</a> lists them live from the registry.
				</p>

				<h2 id="skills">7. Skills</h2>
				<p>
					Skills are markdown documents under <code>skills/&lt;name&gt;/SKILL.md</code>
					that the agent can load on demand. See
					<a href={`${base}/skills`}>the skills page</a>.
				</p>

				<h2 id="i18n">8. i18n</h2>
				<p>
					The web UI is translated to 12 languages. Source of truth is
					<code>apps/web/src/i18n/langs/&lt;code&gt;.ts</code>. The
					<code>bun run check:i18n</code> gate ensures every language has every
					top-level key.
				</p>

				<h2 id="quality">9. Quality gates &amp; multi-language</h2>
				<p>
					Out of the box, <code>bun run validate</code> runs <code>typecheck</code>
					(TS), <code>lint</code> (Biome), <code>lint:scss</code> (Stylelint), and
					<code>test</code> (Vitest). The <code>quality</code> plugin exposes
					three MCP tools an agent can call at any time to scope and run
					project-defined gates:
				</p>
				<ul>
					<li><code>get_quality_scopes</code> — list the configured scopes
					and the exact commands each will run. Read-only.</li>
					<li><code>run_quality</code> — run a scope and return
					<code>{ ok, results: [{ command, ok, code, tail }] }</code>.
					Commands are spawned via <code>shell</code>; the runner
					measures the real exit code, never throws, and is cancellable.</li>
					<li><code>quality_cancel</code> — abort any in-flight run by PID
					(or all) instead of waiting for the timeout.</li>
				</ul>
				<p>
					<strong>The architecture is already language-agnostic.</strong> The
					core defines <code>IValidationCommand = { command, expect }</code>
					and <code>IValidationMatrix = { scopes: Record&lt;string, IValidationCommand[]&gt; }</code>
					(both re-exported from <code>@mcp-vertex/core/public</code>), and the
					JSON schema in <code>mcp-vertex.config.json</code> validates the
					shape. Any command that returns exit-code 0 works — <code>tsc</code>,
					<code>mypy</code>, <code>cargo check</code>, <code>go vet</code>,
					<code>ruff</code>, <code>detekt</code>, <code>shellcheck</code>, etc.
				</p>
				<p>Three sources of scopes, in precedence order:</p>
				<ol>
					<li>Plugin options — <code>quality.scopes = { feature: ["..."] }</code>.</li>
					<li><code>mcp-vertex.config.json</code> →
					<code>validationMatrix.scopes</code> (the canonical surface).</li>
					<li>Detected <code>package.json</code> scripts
					(<code>lint</code>, <code>typecheck</code>, <code>test</code>,
					<code>build</code>) folded into one <code>all</code> scope.</li>
				</ol>
				<p>Example — a polyglot project, with both TypeScript and Python
				gates in one config:</p>
				<pre><code>{`{
  "plugins": {
    "quality": { "options": {} }
  },
  "validationMatrix": {
    "scopes": {
      "typecheck": [
        { "command": "tsc --noEmit", "expect": "exit0" },
        { "command": "mypy .",      "expect": "exit0" }
      ],
      "lint": [
        { "command": "biome ci .",  "expect": "exit0" },
        { "command": "ruff check .", "expect": "exit0" }
      ],
      "test": [
        { "command": "vitest run",  "expect": "exit0" },
        { "command": "pytest -q",   "expect": "exit0" }
      ]
    }
  }
}`}</code></pre>
				<p>For Rust and Go, swap the <code>typecheck</code> commands for
				<code>cargo check --all-targets</code> and
				<code>go vet ./...</code> respectively — the runner and schema
				don't care which binary runs, only that exit 0 means "pass". The
				core <strong>does not install</strong> any toolchain; your CI
				image or local dev shell is expected to provide them.</p>
				<p>
					<strong>Trust boundary (M13):</strong> <code>run_quality</code>
					executes whatever the host config says. The commands come from
					<em>your</em> <code>mcp-vertex.config.json</code> or your plugin
					options — so the trust boundary is the host, not the agent. To
					harden a setup where a less-trusted agent can call
					<code>run_quality</code>, restrict which binaries may run with
					an allow/deny policy (enforced <em>before</em> any spawn; a
					blocked command is reported as failed with code 126, never
					executed):
				</p>
				<pre><code>{`{
  "plugins": {
    "quality": {
      "options": {
        "commandPolicy": {
          "allow": ["bun", "npm", "npx", "tsc", "vitest", "biome", "mypy", "ruff", "pytest"],
          "deny":  ["curl", "wget", "bash", "sh"]
        }
      }
    }
  }
}`}</code></pre>
				<p>
					See the <a href={`${base}/plugins`}>plugin index</a> for the
					<code>quality</code> plugin page, and the
					<a href={`${base}/tools`}>tools page</a> for the live registry
					of <code>quality_*</code> tools.
				</p>

				<h2 id="extending">10. Extending mcp-vertex</h2>
				<p>
					Write your own plugin by exporting <code>IMcpPlugin</code> from a
					package and adding it to <code>mcp-vertex.config.json</code>. See the
					<a href="https://github.com/CartagoGit/mcp-vertex/tree/main/examples/custom-plugin">custom-plugin example</a>.
				</p>

				<h2 id="tokens">11. Token budgets</h2>
				<p>
					Every public response shape is measured. <code>overview (compact)</code>
					+ <code>auto_work</code> fits in &lt; 300 tokens. A CI test fails on regression.
					See <a href={`${base}/benchmarks`}>benchmarks</a>.
				</p>

				<h2 id="transitions">12. View transitions</h2>
				<p>
					The site uses Astro View Transitions: navigating cross-fades and the page
					title morphs via <code>transition:name="page-title"</code>. Respects
					<code>prefers-reduced-motion</code>.
				</p>

				<h2 id="faq">13. FAQ</h2>
				<h3>How is this different from the official MCP SDK?</h3>
				<p>
					The official SDK gives you the protocol primitives; mcp-vertex gives you
					a project-agnostic <em>server</em> with a plugin loader, registry, view
					transitions, and a measured token budget.
				</p>
				<h3>Does it work with my IDE?</h3>
				<p>
					Yes — the server is stdio MCP. Any MCP client (VS Code + Copilot Chat,
					Cursor, Windsurf, Claude Desktop, Claude Code, Antigravity, Zed) works.
					See <a href={`${base}/install`}>install</a>.
				</p>
				<h3>Is the core fast?</h3>
				<p>
					Yes. Boot is &lt; 100 ms. <code>overview (compact)</code> returns in
					&lt; 50 ms. Tests run in ~7 s on a clean checkout.
				</p>
			</article>
		</div>
	</section>
</Base>
